30 PART IV. ADDITIONAL MECKLENBURG COUNTY ROADWAY SYSTEMS AND
31 PUBLIC TRANSPORTATION SYSTEMS SALES TAX
32 SECTION 4.1. Title. – This Part is the Mecklenburg County Roadway Systems and
33 Public Transportation Systems Sales Tax Act and may be cited by that name. This Part gives
34 Mecklenburg County an opportunity to obtain an additional source of revenue with which to meet
35 its needs for financing roadway systems and public transportation systems. It provides the County
36 with authority to levy sales and use taxes. All such taxes must be approved in a referendum.
37 SECTION 4.2. Definitions. – The definitions in G.S. 105-164.3, G.S. 105-506.1,
38 and the following definitions apply in this Part:
39 (1) Authority. – A metropolitan public transportation authority created under
40 Article 34 of Chapter 160A of the General Statutes, as enacted by Part V of
41 this act.
42 (2) Eligible municipality. – Any of the following municipalities in Mecklenburg
43 County: the City of Charlotte and the Towns of Cornelius, Davidson,
44 Huntersville, Matthews, Mint Hill, and Pineville.
45 (3) Red Line. – A rail project that includes, at a minimum, service from the center
46 of the City of Charlotte through the towns of Cornelius, Davidson, and
47 Huntersville and, provided that agreement is obtained from applicable local
48 governments outside of Mecklenburg County, continues to a point north of
49 the jurisdiction of the Town of Davidson, and in no event shall the terminus
50 be in the Town of Davidson's jurisdiction unless approved by the Town of
51 Davidson.
House Bill 948-Fifth Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (4) Roadway system. – A roadway together with appurtenances to a roadway
2 which includes, but is not limited to, plans, designs, and related studies;
3 rights-of-way, whether conveyed by deed or easement; construction,
4 maintenance, and improvements to streets and highways, intersections,
5 streetscapes and landscaping, pedestrian facilities, bicycle facilities, parking
6 lots, curbs, gutters, storm drainage, bridges, overpasses, grade crossings, street
7 lighting, and traffic control devices; utility relocations; publicly accessible
8 electric vehicle charging infrastructure, hydrogen fueling infrastructure,
9 propane fueling infrastructure, natural gas fueling infrastructure, and
10 vehicle-to-grid infrastructure; current and emerging intelligent transportation
11 technologies, including the ability of vehicles to communicate with
12 infrastructure, buildings, and other road users; projects that facilitate
13 intermodal connections between emerging transportation technologies, such
14 as magnetic levitation and hyperloop; protective features, including natural
15 infrastructure, to enhance the resilience of a transportation facility; and
16 measures to protect a roadway system from cybersecurity threats.
17 SECTION 4.3. Exemption of Food. – A tax levied under this Part does not apply to
18 the sales price of food that is exempt from tax pursuant to G.S. 105-164.13B or to the sales price
19 of a bundled transaction taxable pursuant to G.S. 105-467(a)(5a).
20 SECTION 4.4.(a) Advisory Referendum. – The Mecklenburg County Board of
21 Commissioners may direct the county board of elections to conduct an advisory referendum
22 within the County on the question of whether a local sales and use tax at the rate of one percent
23 (1%) may be levied in accordance with this Part. The election shall be held in accordance with
24 the procedures of G.S. 163-287. The Board of Commissioners shall hold a public hearing on the
25 question at least 30 days before the date the election is to be held.
26 SECTION 4.4.(b) Ballot Question. – The form of the question to be presented on a
27 ballot for a special election concerning the levy of a tax authorized by this Part shall be:
28 "[ ] FOR [ ] AGAINST
29 One percent (1%) local sales and use taxes, in addition to the current local sales and
30 use taxes, to be used only for roadway systems and public transportation systems."
31 SECTION 4.5. Levy of Tax. – The Board of Commissioners may, by resolution,
32 levy one percent (1%) local sales and use taxes in addition to any other State and local sales and
33 use taxes levied pursuant to law only if all of the following conditions are satisfied:
34 (1) The majority of those voting in a referendum held pursuant to Section 4.4(a)
35 of this Part vote for the levy of the tax.
36 (2) An Authority that includes Mecklenburg County has been established.
37 (3) At least one eligible municipality or an Authority maintains a public
38 transportation system in the County.
39 SECTION 4.6. Administration. – Except as otherwise provided in this Part, the
40 adoption, levy, collection, administration, and repeal of these additional taxes shall be in
41 accordance with Article 39 of Chapter 105 of the General Statutes. Nothing in this Part obligates
42 Mecklenburg County to exercise any power of taxation or restricts the ability of the County to
43 repeal the tax previously levied.
44 SECTION 4.7. Distribution. – The Secretary of Revenue shall, on a monthly basis,
45 distribute to Mecklenburg County the net proceeds of the tax levied under this Part. Mecklenburg
46 County must distribute forty percent (40%) of the net proceeds of a tax levied under this Part as
47 provided in Section 4.8 of this act and sixty percent (60%) of the net proceeds of a tax levied
48 under this Part as provided in Section 4.9 of this act.
49 SECTION 4.8. Roadway Distribution and Use. – Mecklenburg County must
50 distribute forty percent (40%) of the net proceeds of a tax levied under this Part among the eligible
51 municipalities as provided in this section. Each eligible municipality shall annually submit to the
