7 SECTION 4.8A. Each eligible municipality shall use the net proceeds distributed to
8 it under Section 4.8 of this act to supplement and not to supplant or replace existing local
9 expenditures for roadway systems. For purposes of this section, "local expenditures" means
10 expenditures from non-State and nonfederal funds that are not derived from the proceeds of
11 indebtedness issued by the municipality or grants received by the municipality. To comply with
12 this section, each eligible municipality shall, at a minimum, maintain local expenditures for
13 roadway systems at a level that meets or exceeds the average level of local expenditures for
14 roadway systems by the municipality during the 10 fiscal years beginning with the 2014-2015
15 fiscal year and ending with the 2023-2024 fiscal year.
16 SECTION 4.9. Public Transportation Distribution and Use. – Mecklenburg County
17 must distribute sixty percent (60%) of the net proceeds of the tax levied under this Part to the
18 Authority. The Authority shall use the net proceeds distributed to it under this section only for
19 costs associated with financing, acquiring, constructing, operating, and maintaining any
20 combination of real and personal property for a public transportation system, specifically
21 including micro transit services. The Authority may accomplish these purposes by undertaking
22 these activities itself or by entering an interlocal agreement with a municipality in Mecklenburg
23 County that operates a public transportation system to use funds allocated under this section for
24 those purposes as directed by the Authority in the interlocal agreement. An interlocal agreement
25 entered under this section may include a binding commitment on the part of the Authority to
26 allocate all or a portion of these proceeds to the municipality for a defined number of years or
27 until a defined condition is met, such as the satisfaction of any debt that was issued for public
28 transportation systems. In addition, the Authority may enter an agreement with a private entity
29 whereby that entity uses these funds for this purpose as directed by the Authority in the
30 agreement. The net proceeds of a tax levied under this Part that are distributed to the Authority
31 may be included as revenues within the meaning of G.S. 159-81(4), including any modifications
32 of that statute. The following conditions apply to the use of funds distributed under this section:
33 (1) No more than two-thirds of these funds may be used for the capital and
34 operating costs of rail projects over any period of 30 calendar years combined.
35 Compliance with this section is first determined at the end of the first 30-year
36 period, and then annually thereafter based on the previous 30-year period.
37 Nothing in this section will be interpreted to adversely impact the rights of
38 bondholders to any funds distributed or pledged to secure bonds, notes, or
39 other obligations used to finance or refinance real and personal property for a
40 public transportation system.
41 (2) The Authority shall complete at least fifty percent (50%) of the Red Line as
42 evidenced by a scope of work schedule created and submitted by the general
43 contractor or construction manager on the project before the completion of
44 any other rail project, absent the existence or occurrence of force majeure
45 events that delay completion of the Red Line or make completion of the Red
46 Line impracticable. For the purposes of this section, a "scope of work
47 schedule" is defined as a listing of project tasks associated with a project time
48 line that is updated as the Red Line construction project progresses. For the
49 purposes of this section, force majeure events include fire, flood, earthquakes,
50 other elements of nature, acts of war, terrorism, riots, civil disorders,
51 rebellions or revolutions, nuclear or chemical contamination, epidemics,
House Bill 948-Fifth Edition Page 7

