46 PART V. METROPOLITAN PUBLIC TRANSPORTATION AUTHORITY
47 SECTION 5.1. Chapter 160A of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
48 Article to read:
49 "Article 34.
50 "Metropolitan Public Transportation Authority.
51 "§ 160A-900. Title.
Page 8 House Bill 948-Fifth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 This Article shall be known and may be cited as the "Metropolitan Public Transportation
2 Authority Act."
3 "§ 160A-901. Definitions.
4 As used in this Article, unless the context otherwise requires:
5 (1) Authority. – A metropolitan public transportation authority as defined by
6 subdivision (3) of this section.
7 (2) Board of trustees. – The governing board of the authority, in which the general
8 legislative powers of the authority are vested.
9 (3) Metropolitan public transportation authority. – A body corporate and politic
10 organized in accordance with the provisions of this Article for the purposes,
11 with the powers and subject to the restrictions hereinafter set forth.
12 (4) Population. – The number of persons residing in respective areas as defined
13 and enumerated in the most recent decennial federal census.
14 (5) Public transportation system. – Defined in G.S. 105-506.1.
15 (6) Unit of local government. – Any county, city, town, or municipality of this
16 State, and any other political subdivision, public corporation, authority, or
17 district in this State, which is or may be authorized by law to acquire, establish,
18 construct, enlarge, improve, maintain, own, and operate public transportation
19 systems.
20 (7) Unit of local government's chief administrative official. – The county
21 manager, city manager, town manager, or other person by whatever title, in
22 whom the responsibility for the unit of local government's administrative
23 duties is vested.
24 "§ 160A-902. Definition of territorial jurisdiction of authority.
25 An authority may be created for any area of the State that, at the time of creation of the
26 authority, meets all of the following criteria:
27 (1) The area consists of a single county that has a population greater than one
28 million.
29 (2) The county borders another state.
30 (3) The county includes at least one unit of local government that operates a light
31 rail system.
32 "§ 160A-903. Creation of authority.
33 (a) The Board of Commissioners of a county for which an authority may be created as
34 defined in G.S. 160A-902 may by resolution signify its determination to organize an authority
35 under the provisions of this Article. The resolution shall be adopted after a public hearing thereon,
36 notice of which hearing shall be given by publication at least once, not less than 10 days prior to
37 the date fixed for such hearing, in a newspaper having a general circulation in the county. The
38 notice shall contain a brief statement of the substance of the proposed resolution, shall set forth
39 the proposed articles of incorporation of the authority, and shall state the time and place of the
40 public hearing to be held thereof. No county shall be required to make any other publication of
41 such resolution under the provisions of any other law.
42 (b) Each such resolution shall include articles of incorporation which shall set forth all of
43 the following:
44 (1) The name of the authority.
45 (2) A statement that the authority is organized under this Article.
46 (3) The name of the organizing county.
47 (4) A provision stating that an affirmative vote equal to at least seventy-five
48 percent (75%) of the membership of the board of trustees is required to amend
49 the articles of incorporation or to adopt or amend the bylaws of the authority.
50 (c) A certified copy of the resolutions signifying the determination to organize an
51 authority under the provisions of this Article shall be filed with the Secretary of State, together
House Bill 948-Fifth Edition Page 9

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 with proof of publication of the notice of hearing on each of such resolutions. If the Secretary of
2 State finds that the resolution, including the articles of incorporation, conform to the provisions
3 of this Article and that the notices of hearing were properly published, the Secretary shall file the
4 resolutions and proofs of publication and shall issue a certificate of incorporation under the seal
5 of the State and shall record the same in an appropriate book of record. The issuance of a
6 certificate of incorporation by the Secretary of State constitutes the authority a public body and
7 body politic and corporate of the State of North Carolina. The certificate of incorporation is
8 conclusive evidence of the fact that the authority has been duly created and established under the
9 provisions of this Article.
10 (d) When the authority has been duly organized and its officers elected as provided in
11 this Article, the secretary of the authority shall certify to the Secretary of State the names and
12 addresses of officers as well as the address of the principal office of the authority.
13 (e) The authority may become a Designated Recipient pursuant to the Urban Mass
14 Transportation Act of 1964, as amended.
15 "§ 160A-904. Territorial jurisdiction of the authority.
16 (a) The initial territorial jurisdiction of an authority created pursuant to this Article shall
17 be coterminous with the boundaries of the county that organized it.
18 (b) Except as provided by this Article, the jurisdiction of the authority may include all
19 local public passenger transportation operating within the territorial jurisdiction of the authority,
20 but the authority may not take over the operation of any existing public transportation without
21 the consent of the owner.
22 (c) The authority shall not have jurisdiction over public transportation subject to the
23 jurisdiction of and regulated by the Interstate Commerce Commission, nor shall it have
24 jurisdiction over intrastate public transportation classified as common carriers of passengers by
25 the North Carolina Utilities Commission.
26 "§ 160A-905. Membership; officers; compensation.
27 (a) The governing body of an authority is the board of trustees. The initial board of
28 trustees shall consist of 27 members, appointed as provided in this section. For each appointment
29 below, the appointing authority may appoint an alternate that may act in the absence of the
30 primary person appointed. The appointments are as follows:
31 (1) Six members appointed by the board of commissioners of the county that
32 created the authority. Of the members appointed by the board of
33 commissioners, at least one member must live in an unincorporated area of
34 the county and at least one member must have experience owning or operating
35 a small business. For purposes of this subdivision, a "small business" is one
36 that is independently owned and operated, not dominant in its field, and
37 employs fewer than 100 employees on a full-time basis.
38 (2) One member appointed by the governing body of the municipality that has the
39 second largest population of residents that reside in the county.
40 (3) One member appointed by the governing body of the municipality that has the
41 third largest population of residents that reside in the county.
42 (4) One member appointed by the governing body of the municipality that has the
43 fourth largest population of residents that reside in the county.
44 (5) One member appointed by the governing body of the municipality that has the
45 fifth largest population of residents that reside in the county.
46 (6) One member appointed by the governing body of the municipality that has the
47 sixth largest population of residents that reside in the county.
48 (7) One member appointed by the governing body of the municipality that has the
49 seventh largest population of residents that reside in the county.
50 (8) Twelve members appointed by the governing body of the largest municipality
51 in the county that created the authority as follows:
Page 10 House Bill 948-Fifth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 a. At least three of these appointments must be made upon the
2 recommendation of an entity that represents business interests in the
3 county.
4 b. At least one of the remaining nine appointments by the governing body
5 must be an individual that has experience owning or operating a small
6 business as defined in subdivision (1) of this subsection.
7 (9) Two members appointed by the General Assembly, one upon the
8 recommendation of the President Pro Tempore of the Senate and one upon the
9 recommendation of the Speaker of the House of Representatives.
10 (10) One member appointed by the Governor.
11 (b) Members of the board of trustees shall serve for terms of four years, provided that
12 one-half of the initial appointments shall be for two-year terms, to be determined by lot at the
13 first meeting of the board of trustees, except that the initial term of one member appointed by the
14 General Assembly shall be for two years and the initial term of the other member appointed by
15 the General Assembly shall be for four years to be determined by lot at the first meeting of the
16 board of trustees. Initial terms of office shall commence upon approval by the Secretary of State
17 of the articles of incorporation.
18 (c) Reserved for future codification purposes.
19 (c1) No elected official may serve concurrently as a member of the board of trustees.
20 (c2) A lobbyist or an immediate family member of a lobbyist may not serve as a member
21 of the board of trustees. The definitions in G.S. 120C-101 and G.S. 138A-3 apply for purposes
22 of this subsection.
23 (d) Members of the board of trustees shall have demonstrated experience or qualifications
24 in the areas of law, finance, engineering, public transportation, urban planning, logistics,
25 government, architecture, or economic development.
26 (e) Members of the board of trustees shall reside within the territorial jurisdiction of the
27 authority as defined by G.S. 160A-904.
28 (f) Every two years, the board of trustees shall elect from its membership a group of
29 officers, which shall include a chairperson, vice-chairperson, secretary, and treasurer. An election
30 of an officer must be by a majority vote at a meeting where a quorum is present.
31 (g) No trustee may serve for more than two consecutive terms on the board of trustees,
32 but a person who has been a member for two consecutive terms may be reappointed after being
33 off the board of trustees for a period of at least two years. An initial term that is two years or less
34 shall not be counted in determining the limitation on consecutive terms. This limitation applies
35 regardless of whether the appointments are made by the same appointing authority.
36 "§ 160A-906. Expansion of authority.
37 Upon approval of authorizing resolutions by the board of trustees and the board of
38 commissioners of the affected county, the territorial jurisdiction and service area of an authority
39 may be expanded to include a whole county within this State that is contiguous to the then
40 existing territorial jurisdiction of the authority. Each of the authorizing resolutions must receive
41 an affirmative vote equal to at least seventy-five percent (75%) of the membership of the
42 applicable board. The authorizing resolutions shall contain provisions with respect to the
43 following:
44 (1) The date on which the territorial jurisdiction is to be expanded to include the
45 county.
46 (2) The extent to which the composition of the board of trustees may be amended,
47 if at all, due to the addition of the county to the territorial jurisdiction of the
48 authority. The authorizing resolutions shall not eliminate or amend the
49 requirements with respect to appointments to the board of trustees that are
50 provided in G.S. 160A-905. Subsections (b) through (g) of G.S. 160A-905
51 shall apply to any additional appointments to the board of trustees.
