19 "§ 160A-924. Reports to the General Assembly.
20 The authority shall annually submit to the General Assembly, on or before February 1, its
21 annual operating report, including a report of its administrative expenditures, and its audited
22 financial report. In odd-numbered years, the report shall be submitted to the Senate and House
23 Transportation Committees. In even-numbered years, the report shall be submitted to the Joint
24 Legislative Transportation Oversight Committee.
25 "§ 160A-925. Limitations on rail transportation liability.
26 (a) As used in this section:
27 (1) Claim. – A claim, action, suit, or request for damages, whether compensatory,
28 punitive, or otherwise, made by any person or entity against:
29 a. The authority, a railroad, or an operating rights railroad; or
30 b. An officer, director, trustee, employee, parent, subsidiary, or affiliated
31 corporation as defined in G.S. 105-130.2, or agent of the authority, a
32 railroad, or an operating rights railroad.
33 (2) Operating rights railroad. – A railroad corporation or railroad company that,
34 prior to January 1, 2001, was granted operating rights by a State-Owned
35 Railroad Company or operated over the property of a State-Owned Railroad
36 Company under a claim of right over or adjacent to facilities used by or on
37 behalf of the authority.
38 (3) Passenger rail services. – The transportation of rail passengers by or on behalf
39 of the authority and all services performed by a railroad pursuant to a contract
40 with the authority in connection with the transportation of rail passengers,
41 including, but not limited to, the operation of trains; the use of right-of-way,
42 trackage, public or private roadway and rail crossings, equipment, or station
43 areas or appurtenant facilities; the design, construction, reconstruction,
44 operation, or maintenance of rail-related equipment, tracks, and any
45 appurtenant facilities; or the provision of access rights over or adjacent to lines
46 owned by the authority or a railroad, or otherwise occupied by the authority
47 or a railroad, pursuant to charter grant, fee simple deed, lease, easement,
48 license, trackage rights, or other form of ownership or authorized use.
49 (4) Railroad. – A railroad corporation or railroad company, including a
50 State-Owned Railroad Company as defined in G.S. 124-11, that has entered
House Bill 948-Fifth Edition Page 17

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 into any contracts or operating agreements of any kind with the authority
2 concerning passenger rail services.
3 (b) Contracts Allocating Financial Responsibility Authorized. – The authority may
4 contract with any railroad to allocate financial responsibility for passenger rail services claims,
5 including, but not limited to, the execution of indemnity agreements, notwithstanding any other
6 statutory, common law, public policy, or other prohibition against same, and regardless of the
7 nature of the claim or the conduct giving rise to such claim.
8 (c) Insurance Required. –
9 (1) If the authority enters into any contract authorized by subsection (b) of this
10 section, the contract shall require the authority to secure and maintain, upon
11 and after the commencement of the operation of trains by or on behalf of the
12 authority, a liability insurance policy covering the liability of the parties to the
13 contract, a State-Owned Railroad Company as defined in G.S. 124-11 that
14 owns or claims an interest in any real property subject to the contract, and any
15 operating rights railroad for all claims for property damage, personal injury,
16 bodily injury, and death arising out of or related to passenger rail services. The
17 policy shall name the parties to the contract, a State-Owned Railroad
18 Company as defined in G.S. 124-11 that owns or claims an interest in any real
19 property subject to the contract, and any operating rights railroad as named
20 insureds and shall have policy limits of not less than two hundred million
21 dollars ($200,000,000) per single accident or incident, and may include a
22 self-insured retention in an amount of not more than five million dollars
23 ($5,000,000).
24 (2) If the authority does not enter into any contract authorized by subsection (b)
25 of this section, upon and after the commencement of the operation of trains by
26 or on behalf of the authority, the authority shall secure and maintain a liability
27 insurance policy, with policy limits and a self-insured retention consistent
28 with subdivision (1) of this subsection, for all claims for property damage,
29 personal injury, bodily injury, and death arising out of or related to passenger
30 rail services.
31 (d) Liability Limit. – The aggregate liability of the authority, the parties to the contract
32 or contracts authorized by subsection (b) of this section, a State-Owned Railroad Company as
33 defined in G.S. 124-11, and any operating rights railroad for all claims arising from a single
34 accident or incident related to passenger rail services for property damage, personal injury, bodily
35 injury, and death, is limited to two hundred million dollars ($200,000,000) per single accident or
36 incident or to any proceeds available under any insurance policy secured pursuant to subsection
37 (c) of this section, whichever is greater.
38 (e) Effect on Other Laws. – This section shall not affect the damages that may be
39 recovered under the Federal Employers' Liability Act, 45 U.S.C. § 51, et seq., (1908); or under
40 Article 1 of Chapter 97 of the General Statutes.
41 "§ 160A-926. Civil liability.
42 Except as provided in G.S. 160A-925, the authority shall be deemed a city for purposes of
43 civil liability pursuant to G.S. 160A-485. Governmental immunity of the authority is waived to
44 a minimum of twenty million dollars ($20,000,000) per single accident or incident. The authority
45 shall maintain a minimum of twenty million dollars ($20,000,000) per single accident or incident
46 of liability insurance. Participation in a local government risk pool pursuant to Article 23 of
47 Chapter 58 of the General Statutes shall be deemed to be the purchase of insurance for the purpose
48 of this section."
