1 SECTION 6.1. If Mecklenburg County creates a metropolitan public transportation
2 authority under Article 34 of Chapter 160A of the General Statutes, as enacted by Part V of this
3 act, then that Authority is subject to all the provisions of this Part.
4 SECTION 6.2. The Authority shall conduct a study of the issues listed in this section.
5 The Authority may use any source of funding available to it to conduct the studies required by
6 this section. This specifically includes funds provided to the Authority by another unit of
7 government and funds that the Authority receives as a donation or grant from any other public or
8 private source. The Authority shall complete the study required under this section and publish a
9 report no later than January 1, 2026. The Authority shall publish the report and submit copies of
10 the report to the President Pro Tempore of the Senate, the Speaker of the House of
11 Representatives, the Legislative Library, the Mecklenburg County Board of Commissioners, the
12 Charlotte City Council, the Town of Cornelius Board of Commissioners, the Town of Davidson
13 Board of Commissioners, the Town of Huntersville Board of Commissioners, the Town of
14 Matthews Board of Commissioners, the Town of Mint Hill Board of Commissioners, the Town
15 of Mooresville Board of Commissioners, and the Pineville Town Council. The Authority shall
16 study the following issues:
17 (1) Legal and financial considerations with respect to the transfer or use of assets
18 from the City of Charlotte or the Charlotte Area Transportation System
19 (CATS) to the Authority.
20 (2) Legal and financial considerations with respect to outstanding indebtedness
21 issued by the City of Charlotte with respect to CATS to ensure no adverse
22 impacts in relation to the outstanding indebtedness.
23 (3) Legal and financial considerations with respect to agreements and
24 recognitions by the City of Charlotte or CATS with respect to the public
25 transportation system with any federal, State, regional, or local governmental
26 entities.
27 (4) Legal and financial considerations with respect to human resources of a
28 transfer of assets, liabilities, and operations of the public transportation system
29 from the City of Charlotte or CATS to the Authority, including issues related
30 to, but not limited to, employee pensions, retirement plans, and benefits.
31 (5) A recommendation as to whether the transfer of assets, liabilities, and
32 operations of the existing public transportation system to the Authority is
33 feasible and advisable.
34 (6) Any other issue determined to be relevant by the Authority.
35 SECTION 6.3. Reserved.
36 SECTION 6.4. The Authority shall do the following no later than one year after
37 enactment of this act:
38 (1) Adopt bylaws that are consistent with the provisions of Article 34 of Chapter
39 160A of the General Statutes.
40 (2) Establish policies with respect to Board governance, including the adoption
41 of a Code of Ethics for Trustees and key employees and the adoption of a
42 Conflicts of Interest policy.
43 (3) Create a human resources plan. This includes, at a minimum:
44 a. Creating an organizational chart that specifies positions that report
45 directly to the Authority's Board of Trustees.
46 b. Completing the search for direct reports to the Board of Trustees.
47 c. Creating personnel policies and procedures, including those related to
48 employee recruitment and retention, compensation and benefit
49 policies and plans, and an employee code of conduct.
