2 PART IX. STATE FUNDING PROVISIONS
3 SECTION 9.1. It is the intent of the General Assembly not to reduce transportation
4 funding allocations for any municipality in Mecklenburg County as a result of the enactment of
5 this act or the levy of a tax under the provisions of this act. In addition, it is the intent of the
6 General Assembly not to reduce State transportation funding for State projects located in
7 Mecklenburg County as a result of the enactment of this act or the levy of a tax under the
8 provisions of this act. Without specific authorization from the General Assembly, the Department
9 of Transportation may not reduce funding for any transportation projects as a result of this act or
10 the levy of a tax pursuant to Part II, III, or IV of this act.
11 SECTION 9.2. Notwithstanding the provisions of G.S. 136-189.11(f), the
12 Department of Transportation shall not revise highway project selection ratings as provided in
13 that statute based on local funding participation by the City of Charlotte, the Town of Cornelius,
14 the Town of Davidson, the Town of Huntersville, the Town of Matthews, the Town of Mint Hill,
15 or the Town of Pineville.
16 SECTION 9.3. The State Auditor is authorized to conduct audits, in accordance with
17 Article 5A of Chapter 147 of the General Statutes, of a local government or metropolitan public
18 transportation authority in its utilization of net proceeds distributed by the Secretary of Revenue
19 pursuant to Part IV of this act to the extent that a local government or metropolitan public
20 transportation authority uses those net proceeds for local funding shares or local funding
21 contributions for any individual projects which are subject to prioritization pursuant to
22 G.S. 136-189.11, and to make findings that a local government or metropolitan public
23 transportation authority has complied with applicable laws. Findings by the State Auditor shall
24 be submitted to the Joint Legislative Commission on Governmental Operations, Joint Legislative
25 Transportation Oversight Committee, and the Fiscal Research Division. Local governments,
26 metropolitan public transportation authorities, and the Department of Transportation shall give
27 the State Auditor full access to all employees, public financial information and records, and all
28 data necessary to complete the audit and the report. The State Auditor shall submit any findings
29 required by this section, and as otherwise required by law, to the General Assembly within 30
30 days of finalizing the report.
31
32 PART X. EFFECTIVE DATE
33 SECTION 10. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
34 law.
